Priority to those with summer jobs requiring certification and for those wishing to guard at Stanford during the year. Lifeguard characteristics and responsibilities, recognition of hazards and emergencies, patron and facility surveillance, interaction with the public, rescue skills. Community first aid and CPR for the professional rescuer. Bring letter from employer to first class meeting. Fee. Prerequisite: pass swim test (swimmer/advanced swimmer level).nnSpr (Weeks)

Techniques under pressure; small group and team tactics. Fitness for the soccer player. Prerequisites: consent of instructor, tryouts. Fee. (AU)nn Win (Simon)

Continued work on crawl, elementary backstroke, backstroke, and sidestroke. Safety skill work as needed. Introduction to or review of breaststroke. Open turns. Introduction to butterfly, flip turn, and conditioning. Fee. Prerequisites: fair technique in crawl, elementary backstroke, backstroke; some sidestroke and breaststroke; ability to swim approximately 100-200 yards continuously by mixing strokes. Fee. Use of computer for analyzing tennis matches. Assist players and coaches by collecting data on player performance. Prerequisite: consent of instructor. Recommended: excellent knowledge of tennis, background in computers and statistics. (AU)nnAut, Win, Spr (Forood, D. Gould)

Refine and improve skills and game playing strategy in two- and four-person sand volleyball. Must have strong skills and general knowledge of team concepts. Prerequisiste: 160 or consent of the instructor. Fee. (AU)nnSpr, (Kosty)
Introduction to basic skills and game play. For those who have never played or have had limited experience. Fee. (AU)nnSpr (Vargas)

Review of basic exercises and techniques. Emphasis is on individualized programs and learning the use of all available machines and free weights. Further discussion on exercise physiology. Prerequisite: 174 or thorough knowledge of basic weight training principles. Fee. (AU)nnAut, Win, Spr (Staff)

Game improvement through drills and practice in all facets of golf. Utilizing these skills to play, lower scores, and manage the game on and off the course. A separate yoga practice promotes flexibility and balance to improve concentration and focus. Prerequisite: Beginning Golf or equivalent. Fee. (AU)nnWin (Conniff, Miller).
Spr (Buddie)

For non-majors and potential earth scientists. The changing planet presents society with a myriad of problems. How do global climate systems work and how do natural and anthropogenic sources of climate change affect us? Are we running out of energy? What are the consequences of energy use? What are our options? How does plate tectonics affect our daily lives and what is the nature of earthquake hazards in California and the Bay Area? A large-scale system approach to the solid earth, oceans, and atmospheres is taken to address the questions of current and future generations of Stanford students. GER:2a nnAut (Zoback, Arrigo)

Economic sources of environmental problems and alternative policies for dealing with them (technology standards, emissions taxes, and marketable pollution permits). Evaluation of the policies addressing regional air pollution, global climate change, water allocation in the western U.S., and the use of renewable resources. Connections between population growth, economic output, environmental quality, and human welfare. Prerequisite: Economics 50.nnAut (Goulder)nn nnnAut (Goulder)

Introduction to the dynamic basis of physical oceanography. Topics: a general description of the physical environment of the ocean; conservation equations for salt, heat, and momentum; geostrophic flows; wind-driven flows; the Gulf Stream; equatorial dynamics and ENSO; the thermohaline circulation of the deep oceans; and tides. Prerequisite: PHYSICS 53.nnWin (Monismith)

(Graduate students register for 297.) The use of satellite remote sensing and digital image processing techniques to monitor terrestrial land cover and land use change. Data from a range of sensors is used to explore a variety of applications: deforestation, urbanization, and wildfires. Labs include a case study of a local land use issue. Prerequisite: 195, GEOPHYS 40, or consent of instructor.nnSpr (Seto)

Independent research into an aspect of Earth Systems related to the studentÂ’s primary track, carried out after the junior year, during the summer, and/or during the senior year. Student develops own project with faculty supervision, or can see adviser for research ideas. 10-15 page thesis required.nnquarter by arrangement  (Staff)

Ecological, economic, and social dimensions of sustainable agriculture in the context of a growing world population. Focus is on both management and technological approaches and on historical content of agricultural growth and change, organic agriculture, soil and water resource management, nutrient and pest management, biotechnology, ecosystem services, and climate change.nnany quarter (Falcon, Naylor, Matson, Kennedy)

Introduction to the study of earthquakes and volcanoes: earthquake location, magnitude and intensity scales, seismic waves, styles of eruptions and volcanic hazards, tsunami waves, types and global distribution of volcanoes, volcano forecasting. Plate tectonics as a framework for understanding earthquake and volcanic processes. Forecasting; earthquake resistant design; building codes; and probabilistic hazard assessment. For non-majors and potential earth scientists. GER:2bnnAut (Beroza, Segall)

Preference to sophomores. Natural hazards (earthquakes, volcanoes, floods, hurricanes, and fires) affect thousands of people everyday. Twenty years of developments in spaceborne imaging technology monitor and respond to such disasters more rapidly than in the past, saving lives and money. Understanding the physical processes involved allows us to anticipate and plan for mitigation of the consequences. How these tools are applied to natural disasters, and how remotely-sensed data are manipulated and analyzed. nnAut (Zebker)

Geological processes, from local to global, affect people and civilization. The reverse is also true; civilization is beginning to influence the geosphere. The processes experienced at the earthÂ’s surface (catastrophic earthquakes, volcanic eruptions, and longer term atmospheric and climate changes) are linked to what goes on in the earthÂ’s deep interior. How geochemical, geophysical, and biological processes interact over time scales ranging from 4.5 billion years to the nearly instantaneous. Topics: the origin and evolution of the atmosphere and oceans, heat flow and global tectonics and how they have changed over time, geochemical cycles, climate change, catastrophic impacts, and the roles played by organisms. Prerequisite: 1 or 2.nnAut (Paytan, Stebbins, McWilliams)

(Graduate studetns register for 235.) How to observe and interpret physical and biological changes in the oceans using satellite technologies. Topics: principles of satellite remote sensing, classes of satellite remote sensors, converting radiometric data into biological and physical quantities, sensor calibration and validation, interpreting large-scale oceanographic features.nn(Arrigo) alternate years, given 2003-04

Lectures and workshops on the structural and stratigraphic interpretation of seismic reflection data, emphasizing hydrocarbon traps in two and three dimensions on industry data, including workstation-based interpretation. Lectures only, 1 unit. Prerequisite: 182, or consent of instructor.nnSpr (Klemperer, Graham) alternate years, not given 2003-04
Research in interdisciplinary problems involving the state and movement of fluids in the earthÂ’s crust. Content varies each quarter.nn(Nur)
Research in transmission and reflection tomography, including topics on forward modeling, inversion, and data acquisition.nn(Harris)

Hands-on experience with ESRIÂ’s Arc-View GIS packages. Topics: setting up geographic databases and manipulating spatial data, including database query and analysis. Hands-on computer-based exercises using sample datasets on workstations. Guest lectures on GIS applications in the environmental, geological, and biological sciences; and in town planning.nnWin (Klemperer)

Experimental, observational, or theoretical honors project and thesis in geophysics under supervision of a faculty member. Students who elect to do an honors thesis should begin planning it no later than Winter Quarter of the junior year. Prerequisites: superior work in the earth sciences and approval of the department.nnAut, Win, Spr, Sum (Staff)

The study and application of seismic-acoustic waves in and around boreholes for application to sonic well logging, crosswell seismic profiling, and vertical seismic profiling. Topics: forward modeling, seismogram interpretation, data processing, imaging, and inversion. Applications from reservoir and site characterization studies and reservoir monitoring. Prerequisite: consent of instructor.nn(Harris) alternate years, given 2003-04

Topics include radar system elements, the radar equation and signal to noise ratio, signal and image processing, range/Doppler algorithms, interferometric measurements. Applications to crustal deformation, topographic mapping, velocities of ice sheets and glaciers, polarimetry and terrain analysis. Computational labs give hands-on-experience with real data.nn(Zebker) alternate years, given 2003-04
Research in interdisciplinary problems involving the state and movement of fluids in the earthÂ’s crust. Content varies each quarter.nn(Nur)
Research in transmission and reflection tomography, including topics on forward modeling, inversion, and data acquisition.nn(Harris)

Basic theorems in elastodynamics, GreenÂ’s functions, attenuation, wave propagation in layered media, ray theory, seismic moment tensors, finite-source effects, kinematics and dynamics of earthquakes, engineering aspects of seismology.nnWin (Beroza) alternate years, not given 2003-04

This course emphasizes the use of accounting information for internal planning and control purposes.  This orientation contrasts with financial accounting where the focus is on accounting disclosures for parties external to the firm.nnnThe course is intended for individuals who will make business decisions and evaluate the performance of business units using data obtained from the accounting system.nnnThe first part of the course covers the vocabulary and mechanics of cost accounting, issues involved in the design of a cost accounting system, and the role of management accounting in decisions concerning resource allocation.  Included in this are discussions of capacity costs, inter-departmental allocations, and activity-based management in both manufacturing and service environments.  We will pay particular attention to various (unintended) dysfunctional consequences of traditional accounting systems, as well as possible solutions to these problems.  nnnThe second part of the course examines the process of evaluating the performance of individuals, business units and firms.  Included in this are issues related to transfer prices and measures of productivity.  We will study the optimal choice of performance metrics for incentive purposes, and analyze the rationale behind the balanced scorecard.  Finally, we will examine methods of estimating cost functions using accounting data, leading to the study of benchmarking procedures, i.e., the process of identifying the most and least productive firms in industries.

This case-based course is intended to enhance students' ability to determine the financial statement effects and the implications for financial reporting of business performance related to mergers, acquisitions, and other corporate structure changes, such as leveraged buy-outs, restructurings, joint ventures, leveraged recapitalizations, and corporate reorganizations. The content and instruction are intended to provide a level of understanding and competence appropriate for general managers faced with making decisions regarding such financial transactions and for investment analysts and others faced with making investment decisions based on financial reporting information provided by firms involved in such transactions. Thus, the course is recommended for anyone planning a career that will involve issuing or analyzing financial statements of for-profit entities engaging in financial transactions that affect corporate structure, such as careers in corporate top management, investment analysis, or banking.

The purpose of this three-quarter seminar is to facilitate the student's conception and execution of substantive individual research. It provides a vehicle for supplementing and integrating the student's knowledge of basic research tools and methods, as well as an exposure to the dimensions of contemporary research in the field of accounting. A610 focuses on the theory of managerial accounting and auditing. A611 focuses on empirical tests of financial accounting theory. A612 focuses on the theory of financial accounting and regulated disclosure. Prerequisite: Consent of the instructors.

This seminar relates major international economic issues to management capability in developing countries.  The emphasis is on the intersections among private management, public management, the World Bank, and International Monetary Fund in managing policies of international trade and international investment.  At a minimum, students should acquire from this seminar:nn1) a framework of analysis for monitoring the progress of a developing countrynn2) the ability to write a country economic reportnn3) judgment on the effectiveness of trade policiesnn4) judgment on the effectiveness of balance of payments policiesnn5) judgment on how public management affects private management.nnClass discussions will focus on analytics, while policy briefings will be applied and policy-oriented.  There will be three policy briefing sessions.  Small groups will select two of the three following policy briefings: a 'hands on' negotiation of foreign direct investment, formulation of a strategy for export promotion, identification of effective remedial policies for international currency crises.nnDuring the last two weeks, there will be presentations of small group or individual work products that have been of the students' own choice, or suggested by the instructor.nnSpecial materials will be distributed.  No exams.  Grading based on seminar participation, policy briefings, and final work product.
Need approval from sponsoring faculty member and GSB Registrar.

E600. Microeconomic Analysis I (Kreps)nnThis course provided an introduction to the foundations of modern microeconomic theory.Topics include the model of consumer choice, with and without uncertainty, demand theory, social choice and efficiency, perfect markets, general equilibrium (static and dynamic), monopoly, and oligopoly.

The instructor and, on a rotating basis, other members of the GSB economics faculty will discuss methods for doing research in economics. Discussion will focus on selecting topics for research, building on existing literature while making original contributions, choosing the appropriate modeling technique, identifying the best empirical strategies, combining theory and evidence, learning when a paper is finished, and providing general tips on how to do successful research. The course will help the student choose a thesis topic and write a successful dissertation. It will also provide a foundation for research that the junior faculty member will be conducting during the first few years following graduate school. nnnThe course, which will meet for 90 minutes once per week, will run throughout the year with a continuing grade. During the Autumn and Winter Quarters, the faculty will present papers and material for discussion. During the Spring term, most of the time will be spent on student discussions and critiques of important papers in the economics literature and on structuring student research papers. This course is recommended for economics PhD students.

This course covers the foundations of corporate finance and uses these foundations to analyze many of the important financial decisions made within firms and other institutions. Some of the topics covered include the valuation of fixed-income securities and stocks, capital budgeting and the choice of investment projects, the optimal capital structure of the firm and how it is affected by taxes, the notion of market efficiency, the valuation of options and other derivative securities and the use of derivative securities in corporate finance.

This course considers a variety of fixed-income securities from the standpoint of investors, issuers, and financial intermediaries.  A conceptual foundation is laid, involving the mathematics of fixed-income cash flows, price-yield relationship, measures of price sensitivity, inflation, optionality, currency risk, default risk, liquidity risk, and tax influences.  Throughout, concepts are applied to actual situations, both in the current market and in cases, in an effort to understand valuation, arbitrage efficiency, and how a particular security might be used by portfolio managers, issuers, and broker/dealers.  The course is reasonably broad, and embraces spot markets, repo markets, forward and futures markets, options markets, LIBOR markets, and currency markets, and the interplay between the fixed-income markets and the macro-economic conditions.

This course builds on the valuation principles learned in F220 and applies them, together with new methods of analysis, to financial management issues within a corporation.  Topic areas include:  the creation of value through required returns; corporate finance theory; dividend policy; exchange rate risk management; tools of financial analysis (financial ratios, source and use statements, pro-formas, cash budgeting, and sustainable growth modeling) applied to situations involving short-, intermediate-, and long-term financing; financial distress; convertible securities; lease financing; mergers and acquisitions; and leverage buyouts.  Cases are the primary vehicle for instruction, where both concepts and applications are stressed.  The course is tightly structured around analysis and reaching a decision.

The Investment Seminar--"Global Principal Investing" is a seminar on selected topics in masterful investing in publicly traded and private equity/venture capital investments, with focus on the principal's point of view.  We also study hedge funds.  We meet with outstanding investors.  The scope is global.  Professor McDonald is a founding director of the largest international investment fund.  The prerequisite is Finance 321-Investment Management and Entrepreneurial Finance.

This course is an introduction to multiperiod models in finance, mainly pertaining to optimal portfolio choice and asset pricing. The course begins with discrete-time models for portfolio choice and security prices, and then moves to a continuous-time setting. The topics then covered include the Black-Scholes model of asset pricing and some of its extensions, models of the term structure of interest rates, valuation of corporate securities, portfolio choice in continuous-time settings, and finally, general-equilibrium asset pricing models. Students should have had some previous exposure to general equilibrium theory and some basic courses in investments. Strong backgrounds in calculus, linear algebra, and probability theory are recommended. Problem assignments are frequent and, for most students, demanding. Prerequisite: F620 or permission of instructor.

The underlying assumption of this course is that creativity is essential to happiness, health and success in business and life. Creativity is within everyone, and this seminar goes deep into the thought processes which relate to everyday creativity. The model of a "Hero's Journey" is used as a metaphor for the creative process. Students are given many opportunities to experience and develop their own style of creativity and are required to use heuristics which can help make creativity a solid part of their everyday decision making repertoire. The goal is to make one's life a "work of art." Course format employs lecture, practical application and class discussion. A special feature of the course this quarter will be the use of the CIB interactive software developed by Professor Ray and others. Students will be required to use this software in place of class sessions in certain parts of the course. Prerequisites are an open mind plus willingness to be introspective, enjoy taking personal risks, and put in substantial work. Students are required to attend regularly and use the CIB software, keep a personal journal, review a relevant book, submit brief weekly papers reflecting on their experience with the course materials, and complete a two-part final project consisting of a written analysis and a creative representation of their own creativity in business.
Special Topics: Business Research

This course is elected as soon as a student is ready to begin research for the dissertation, usually shortly after admission to candidacy. To register, a student must obtain permission from the faculty member who is willing to supervise the research.

This course examines the design and implementation of human resource (HR) management systems in multinational companies. The course will focus on four major issues faced by such companies: (1) the recruitment, selection, compensation and career management of global employees;  (2) the integration of expatriate and local employees into global organizations;  (3) adjusting HR practice to the external environment of the employment relationship (including legal and cultural variations in HR practice); and (4) the use of HR to develop global organizational learning systems. The course will draw on the experience of U.S., Japanese, and European corporations establishing HRM systems in industrialized, transition and developing economies.

The objectives of this course are to introduce students to the substantive and procedural aspects of marketing management and to sharpen skills for critical analytical thinking and effective communication. Specifically, the goals are to introduce students to marketing strategy and to the elements of marketing analysis: customer analysis, competitor analysis, and company analysis; to familiarize students with the elements of the marketing mix (product strategy, pricing, advertising and promotion, and distribution), and to enhance problem solving and decision-making abilities in these operational areas of marketing; and to provide students with a forum (both written and verbal) for presenting and defending their own recommendations, and for critically examining and discussing the recommendations of others.
Need approval from sponsoring faculty member and GSB Registrar.

Brand Planning is an advanced MBA reading seminar (aimed for second year MBAs) that addresses branding decisions faced by companies.  Its basic objectives are: 1) to explore important issues in planning and evaluating brand strategies; 2) to provide exposure to some theories, models, and other tools to make better branding decisions; and 3) to provide a forum (oral and written) for you to apply these principles.  Particular emphasis is placed in the course on understanding psychological principles at the customer level that will improve managerial decision-making with respect to brands.  nnSeminar Outlinenn	Day 1: Overview: Understanding Brandnn	Day 2: Crafting the Brandnn	Day 3: Building the Brandnn	Day 4: Managing the Brand nn	Day 5: Brand AuditsnnSeminar Structure: nnFor each session, a range of articles on brand (e.g., what brand is, why/when is it important, how to measure its value, understanding brand architecture) will be assigned, as well as several additional background articles that you might want to read at a later date.  To complement the readings to be discussed in class will be a series of exercises that allow you to get hands-on experience to some of the qualitative and quantitative insights on crafting, building and managing brands.  Finally, due on the last day of class, you -  in a small group setting - will do a "brand audit" on a particular brand/service.  Short presentations of this audit will be done during the final week of seminar.  Grading: optional pass/fail for this one unit seminar.

This course is elected as soon as a student is ready to begin research for the dissertation, usually shortly after admission to candidacy. To register, a student must obtain permission from the faculty member who is willing to supervise the research.

This course is designed to give students an appreciation for the management issues surrounding the development and use of information technology (IT) in organizations. Its focus is on the managerial and organizational issues raised by new Informational Technologies such as the Internet.

Building on the foundation established in T262 (Operations), T363 will focus on the business processes through which "real work" is accomplished, such as order fulfillment, product development, and customer service. We will discuss fundamental ideas embodied in the total quality management, time-based competition, and business process reengineering movements. Specific topics include: capacity management, integrated work, the impact of variability on process performance, statistical process control, dynamic flow management, time compression, performance measurement systems, and inter-firm coordination. Cases and examples are drawn from a variety of industries, including services, manufacturing, and health care. About one-third of the material is related to tools of process analysis, including several computer assignments. Linear programming and queuing analysis (covered in T245 and T262, respectively) will reappear in T363, but our emphasis is on the business context rather than modeling per se, and the mathematical demands made on students will be modest. About one-half of the class time will be devoted to case discussions. There will be five graded assignments during the quarter, (four group assignments and one individual), plus a few other exercise summaries to be handed in. The assignments will include case analyses, computer simulations, and hands-on simulation exercises. At the instructor's discretion, a group project (for three or four students) with an actual operating unit may be undertaken as a separate, two-unit course on a mandatory pass/fail basis.

This course is designed to introduce incoming students to the structures and processes that affect group performance as well as some of the common pitfalls associated with working in teams.  Topics include understanding team culture, fostering creativity and coordination, making group decisions, and dealing with a variety of personalities. Students will participate in a number of group exercises to illustrate principles of team work and to give students practice diagnosing team problems and taking action to improve total team performance.

Conflict is inherent in organizations. Conflict arises whenever independent parties-individuals, departments, organizations-must secure an agreement. Parties involved face a decision between competitive and cooperative solutions: Will competition bring a favorable result or will it escalate to dysfunctional levels? Will cooperation foster a valuable working relationship or will it leave an underlying problem unresolved? This course presents a variety of frameworks for analyzing conflicts and techniques for resolving conflicts. Many dimensions of conflict are discussed, including relevant psychological, interpersonal, organizational, and cultural dynamics. This course reviews strategy and tactics in various conflict resolution procedures, including bargaining, distributive and integrative negotiation, mediation, and arbitration. A conceptual understanding is of little use, however, without an understanding of how to put strategy and tactics into practice. To this end, considerable emphasis will be placed on exercises and role-play simulations of conflicts designed to develop students' negotiation skills.
Need approval from sponsoring faculty member and GSB Registrar.

This seminar asks why has it been so difficult to change working environments so more women find satisfying careers.  We will examine a variety of small and large-scale gender equity organizational change efforts to determine what works and what doesn't.  The seminar will use a combination of teaching methods.  Each class will begin with an introductory lecture and discussion introducing key ideas from the research literature.  Readings will include a few scholarly readings, as well as a few papers written for an executive audience.  Each class session will also include a case-based discussion or exercise or a visit from a guest executive who is currently leading an organizational change effort.  A visit to a nearby organization, working effectively on these issues, may be arranged.  Instructors' permission required.

Over the past decade or so, sociologists and organizational scholars have increasingly come to recognize that networks are not simply relevant as conduits for the flow of information and resources. In addition, networks are critical determinants of identity -- shaping preferences and influencing perceptions of the qualities that inhere in actors. Drawing from a broad array of intellectual traditions, such as social exchange theory, role theory, as well as economic and historical sociology, this course considers research that informs the link between networks and identity.

This course addresses managerial issues in the social, political, and legal environments of business. Cases and readings emphasize strategies to improve the performance of companies in light of their multiple constituencies. Cases are set in both international and U.S. environments. Topics include integrated strategy, activists and the media, legislation affecting business, regulation and antitrust, intellectual property, Internet privacy, and international trade policy.

This course has three main objectives. The first is to analyze the nature of the EU political system and how it works. The focus will be on the interaction between the Union, member states, organized interests and  public opinion. The second is to examine the major policies of the EU , both those that affect business directly such as competition or cohesion policies and those who shape the European and national business environments (market de-regulation). Whenever  appropriate comparisons will be made  between  different approaches to policies in the EU and the US, such as in the realm of  anti-trust law (the GE-Honeywell case) or  agricultural trade ( the issue of  GMO).The third objective is to study the consequences of the monetary union and of  the planned expansion eastwards. Both developments  are bound to change significantly in the medium term the nature of the Union and its policies. Overall students will come out of this course with a useful framework for understanding the relationship between political developments and economic change in the context of a unique  historical process of regional integration which carries a significant lesson for other parts of the world.

This course is elected as soon as a student is ready to begin research for the dissertation, usually shortly after admission to candidacy. To register, a student must obtain permission from the faculty member who is willing to supervise the research.

This course is offered for students who at some time may want to undertake an entrepreneurial career by pursuing opportunities leading to partial or full ownership and control of a business. The course deals with case situations from the point of view of the entrepreneur/manager rather than the passive investor. Most cases involve visitors or videotapes, since the premise is that opportunity and action have large idiosyncratic components. The students must assess opportunity and action in light of the perceived capabilities of the individuals and the nature of the environments they face. The course is integrative and will allow students to apply many facets of their business school education

Many of America's most successful entrepreneurial companies have been substantially influenced by professionally managed venture capital. This relationship is examined from both the entrepreneur's and the venture capitalist's perspective. From the point of view of the entrepreneur, the course considers how significant business opportunities are identified, planned, and built into real companies; how resources are matched with opportunity; and how, within this framework, entrepreneurs seek capital and other assistance from venture capitalists or other sources. From the point of view of the venture capitalist, the course considers how potential entrepreneurial investments are evaluated, valued, structured and enhanced; how different venture capital strategies are deployed; and how venture capitalists raise and manage their own funds. nnThe course includes a term project where students, working in teams, prepare a realistic, action-oriented business plan to either launch a new enterprise or to direct a young business to profitability and/or growth. A special effort is made to take advantage of Stanford's close proximity to the venture capital and entrepreneurial community by making extensive use of guest speakers. Students work in teams of 3-4 students to produce a business plan.

In this course, our purpose will be to explore issues in managing a growing and/or changing organization. To this end, three general questions will guide our inquiry: 1) How do the opportunities for growth and fundamental change vary with a firm's strategy and its ecology? 2) What challenges generally arise as firms grow and change, and how can these be met? The answers to these questions depend on the characteristics of your firm and of its competitive environment. In a small firm, one must create an initial growth trajectory, and then adapt the firm and its strategies to the requirements of larger-scale operation. By contrast, in a larger, more established firm, the key challenge is to sustain growth -- through revitalizing current businesses or possibly by expanding into new areas. The challenge in both contexts is for managers to design the organization as a system that can grow successfully. Doing so requires sophisticated understanding of processes of organizational change.

The crisis in Asia - after many years of rapid growth - raises a number of questions about the relative merits of alternative paths of development, and about our capacity to anticipate the future. If the current crisis has created very dramatic socio-economic situations in several Asian countries, it has also provided - beyond the change process - many opportunities for foreign investors, for transfer of technology, and for different types of partnerships. In this context the "challenge" to operate within the mosaic of Asian cultures - experiencing great turbulence - is more actual than ever. The course will analyze the complex interdependence between "culture", management philosophies, corporate strategies and the current dynamics of socio-economic development. Alternative models will be used to understand this interdependence, while the course will emphasize the skills necessary to handle effectively (specific) problems associated with work in different Asian cultures. Starting from today's situation in the region, the first part of the course will analyze the relationship between values and economic and managerial behavior (e.g. Confucian ethics and socio-economic development, Islam and corporate behavior in Malaysia, ideology and practices in Overseas Chinese organizations). The course will then discuss the relationship between culture and human resource management (e.g. recruiting staff and training for technology transfer in Thailand, expatriate profile for Japan, Korea and China, motivating and managing career development in Hong Kong and Singapore, role of "Third Country Nationals" in the ASEAN region). The course will then deal with "sensitive issues such as nepotism, bribery and corruption, race and religion as they affect managerial attitudes and corporate behavior (with examples from Vietnam, the Philippines and China). Cases of US, European and Asian corporations operating in the region will help participants to have concrete and current examples of the difficulties and the conditions of success in operating through the different cultures of the Asia Pacific region.

In this seminar, we will look at competition in a number of different markets: we will look at emerging art markets, contested occupational markets, venture capital and investment banking markets, as well as the market for corporate control.  In examining each of these markets we will be concerned with the same basic issue: the role of status and identity in shaping market outcomes.nnnIndeed, the central premise of this seminar is that the status and/or identity of an actor is a fundamental determinant of the opportunities and constraints that a market actor faces.  However, conventional models of markets tend to downplay the role of status and identity and, in the process, miss some important dynamics underlying competition.  Drawing on sociological work over the last twenty years (including some of the instructor's own research), this seminar aims to provide some insight into this overlooked aspect of market competition.  nnnAmong the questions that we will consider are: What tactics do market actors use to preserve or enhance their market status?  What role do third parties in markets - like analysts, journalists, or critics - play in the establishment of identities?  How does a market actor's status and identity impact on its ability to learn and innovate and, accordingly, on the strategies that the actor can or should pursue?

Priority given to undergraduates and masterÂ’s degree students. Basic theories and concepts in leadership and group process. Topics: leadership and personal values building, shared vision, group problem solving, leadership styles, giving and receiving feedback, decision making, and power and influence. Interactive and experiential, and requires weekly reading and journal writing. Enrollment limited to 16. (SSPEP)nnWin (Porteus) not given 2002-03

(Same as Symbolic Systems 100, Linguistics 144, Philosophy 190.) The history, foundations, and accomplishments of the cognitive sciences, including presentations by leading Stanford researchers in artificial intelligence, linguistics, philosophy, and psychology. Overview of issues addressed in the Symbolic Systems major.nn4 units, Spr (Greeno, Taylor)

Preference to sophomores. Explanations for group and individual differences in test performance have been controversial this century, right up to current debates over affirmative action. The purposes and the logic of various testing programs, including classroom testing, admissions testing, and state and national testing programs. The meanings of reliability, validity, bias, and fairness in testing, developing the notion of validity argument as a conceptual tool for analyzing testing applications. Paper on some educational testing application.nnWin (Haertel)
